<section xml:id="sec-factoring-quadratic-trinomials" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Factoring Quadratic Trinomials</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>Factoring quadratic trinomials is arguably the single most used skill in high-school mathematics, being used in uncountably many high-school (and college) math problems. In this way, it is very important to master. However, unfortunately, it is among the least important and least useful topic "in the real world".</p>

    <p>The goal is to factor any expression of the form <m>ax^2 + bx + c</m>, where <m>a, b, c</m> are any integers.</p>
    <p>
      <ul>
        <li>First, we'll start with a simpler case, when <m>a = 1</m>.</li>
        <li>Then, we'll consider the more difficult case, when <m>a \neq 1</m>.</li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <subsection>
    <title>Factoring <m>x^2+bx+c</m> (Sum and Product Method)</title>
    <example>
      <p>We want to take an expression like <m>x^2 + 7x + 6</m>, and rewrite it as <m>(x + \quad)(x + \quad)</m>. The question is: how to choose the two numbers to put in the brackets. To do this, let's observe the pattern for how expansions work. Consider the expansion of <m>(x+3)(x+5)</m>,</p>
      <md>
        <mrow>(x+3)(x+5) \amp = x^2 + 3x + 5x + 15</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = x^2 + 8x + 15</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>Here are some other expansions,</p>
      <md>
        <mrow>(x+2)(x+3) \amp = x^2 + 5x + 6</mrow>
        <mrow>(x+7)(x-2) \amp = x^2 + 5x - 14</mrow>
        <mrow>(x-5)(x-3) \amp = x^2 - 8x + 15</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>Observe how expanding the left side leads to the right side. On the right side, there are always 3 terms: <m>x^2</m>, an <m>x</m> term, and a constant number term. Also, to get the coefficient of the middle <m>x</m> term, you <em>add</em> the two numbers in the brackets. To get the last constant term, you <em>multiply</em> those two numbers. In other words,</p>
      <md>
        <mrow>(x+3)(x+5) \amp = x^2 + 3x + 5x + 15</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = x^2 + \left(\text{sum of 3 and 5}\right)x + \left(\text{product of 3 and 5} \right)</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = x^2 + 8x + 15</mrow>
      </md>
    </example>
    <p>In general, if we multiply two factors together, say <m>x+a</m> and <m>x+b</m>, we get,</p>
    <md>
      <mrow>(x+a)(x+b) \amp = x^2 + ax + bx + ab</mrow>
      <mrow>\amp = x^2 + (a + b)x + ab</mrow>
    </md>
    <p>
      <ul>
        <li>The first term is always <m>x^2</m>.</li>
        <li>The coefficient of the middle term is the <em>sum</em> of <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>.</li>
        <li>The last term is the <em>product</em> of <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>.</li>
      </ul>
    </p>
    <p>In summary,</p>
    <md>
      <mrow>\boxed{(x + a)(x + b)
      = x^{2}
      + \underbrace{(a + b)}_{\substack{\text{coefficient of }x\\\text{is the sum }a + b}}\,x
      + \underbrace{ab}_{\substack{\text{constant term}\\\text{is the product }ab}}}</mrow>
    </md>
    <p>This leads to a general rule for factoring an expression of the form <m>x^2 + bx + c</m>.</p>
    <md>
      <mrow>\boxed{\text{To factor } x^2+bx+c \text{ , find two numbers that multiply to } c \text{ and add to } b}</mrow>
    </md>

    <exercise>
      <statement>Factor <m>x^2 + 7x + 12</m>.</statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>Factor <m>x^2 - 7x + 6</m>.</statement>
    </exercise>

    <p>In summary,</p>
    <p>
      <ol>
        <li>Arrange the trinomial in descending power order <m>x^2 + bx + c</m> (if needed)</li>
        <li>Go through the pairs of number which multiply to <m>c</m>, and check if they add to <m>b</m>.</li>
        <li>If they do, then write it as <m>(x+ \quad)(x + \quad)</m></li>
      </ol>
    </p>

    <exercise>
      <statement>Factor each quadratic expression.
        <p>
          <ol marker="a">
            <li><m>x^2 + 3x + 2</m></li>
            <li><m>x^2 - 6x + 8</m></li>
