  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Factoring Out the GCF First Before the Cross Method</title>
    <example>
      <statement>Consider the quadratic, <md><mrow>3x^2 + 30x + 75</mrow></md></statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Here, the numbers are kinda large, but we can still use the cross method. After some trial and error, the correct combination is,
        </p>
        <image width="50%">
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[baseline=(M.base)]
                \node (M) at (0,0)    {$3x$};
                \node (P) at (0,-1)   {$x$};
                \node (N) at (1.5,0)  {$15$};
                \node (Q) at (1.5,-1) {$5$};
                \draw (M) -- (Q);
                \draw (P) -- (N);
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
        <md>
          <mrow>= (3x + 15)(x + 5)</mrow>
        </md>
        <p>However, notice that <m>3x + 15</m> also contains a common factor of 3, so we should factor it out.</p>
        <md>
          <mrow>\amp = 3(x + 5)(x + 5)</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = 3(x + 5)^2</mrow>
        </md>
        <p>Instead, it is easier to first factor out the common factor of 3,</p>
        <md>
          <mrow>3x^2 + 30x + 75 \amp = 3 \brac{x^2 + 10x + 25}</mrow>
        </md>
        <p>Then, factoring the remaining <m>x^2 + 10x + 25</m> only uses the sum and product method, and has smaller numbers to work with,</p>
        <md>
          <mrow>\amp = 3 (x + 5)(x + 5)</mrow>
        </md>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <p>
      In general, it is easier to first factor out the GCF (greatest common factor), if there is one, before using the cross method. This makes the numbers you have to work with smaller, making it easier to find the factors.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Summary of Factoring <m>ax^2 + bx + c</m></title>
    <p>
      <ol>
        <li>Always start by factoring out any common factor (the GCF)</li>
        <ul>
          <li>If the leading coefficient is negative, factor out <m>-1</m> from all terms.</li>
        </ul>
        <li>
          <ul>
            <li>If <m>a = 1</m> (<m>x^2 + bx + c</m>), then find two numbers that multiply to <m>c</m> and add to <m>b</m>.</li>
            <li>If <m>a \neq 1</m> (<m>ax^2 + bx + c</m>), then use the cross method.</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>To check your answer, you can expand (FOIL) and check if you get back the original expression.</li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </subsection>
</section>
